      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Great question! After Prophase, we move on to Metaphase. During Metaphase, the chromosomes line up at the metaphase plate, which is an imaginary plane equidistant from the two poles of the cell. The spindle fibers attach to the centromeres of the chromosomes, holding them in place. This is like a tug-of-war game where the chromosomes are the players, and the spindle fibers are the ropes, keeping them centered and ready for the next move. Metaphase ensures that each new cell will receive one copy of each chromosome, much like ensuring each player gets an equal share of the prize.",
